										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2>What is a Marketing Funnel?</h2>
<p><strong>The marketing funnel is the path users take during their journey with you</strong>, from introduction to, ideally, conversion. You are trying to get users to a specific destination, and in order to get them there, youâ€™ll need to leave signposts and rest houses along the way to keep them on track.</p>
<p>Letâ€™s face it, funnels can be awfully boring (unless weâ€™re discussing the fried carnival variety). Thatâ€™s why Iâ€™m using an ice cream cone for my funnel breakdown! For those of you losing interest, stay with me, for there are tasty treats involved.</p>
<p>Introducing the <strong>Ice Cream Cone Marketing Funnel!</strong> Letâ€™s dig in!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="5cab26f4-7d6e-45fc-9bba-ceb8673f82f3" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/marketing-funnel-2.png" alt="marketing funnel" width="688" height="830" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Although funnels look like pretty stable objects, in the marketing word, itâ€™s still easy for users to fall through the cracks and wander off the trail, where they can get eaten by bears (i.e. your competitors).</p>
<p>In this post, Weâ€™ll talk about various stages of the marketing funnel and how you can guide users towards their final destination (the good kind of final destination â€“ not the <em>Final Destination</em> where everyone dies).</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="fb3b5e4b-c94f-4f03-929f-b74373e062f5" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/final-destintation.jpg" alt="final destination" width="180" height="261" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Would you believe this gem only got a 33% on Rotten Tomatoes?</em></p>
<h2>Top Of The Funnel: Get People Interested In You</h2>
<p>At the top of our ice cream cone funnel, itâ€™s all about seduction. The sprinkles, the whipped cream, the chocolate sauce â€“ itâ€™s all there to entice users.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="4a4291c4-8633-4f0e-ad06-0eb54e2a297d" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/marketing-sales-funnel.jpg" alt="marketing sales funnel" width="640" height="480" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>In marketing, seduction appears in the form of <strong>fun and informative free content</strong>. The specific media of this top-funnel content can vary depending on your industry. Here are some examples of top-of-funnel content:</p>
<ul>
<li>Engaging <a href="/blog/ws/2015/01/05/marketing-videos">marketing videos</a></li>
<li>Informative ebooks and how-to articles</li>
<li>Pinterest-style quote images</li>
<li>Listicles</li>
</ul>
<p>Still, just <em>having</em> your top-level content isnâ€™t enough. No one is going to go crazy over that delicious ice cream cone if they donâ€™t even see it.</p>
<p>To showcase your top-funnel content to your audiences, youâ€™ll get involved with:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Social Media</strong>. Build your audience on social media and broadcast your killer content across social networks.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>PPC and SEO</strong>: Get users to your content through <a href="/blog/ws/2015/04/30/seo-basics">organic SEO</a> and paid Google searches (with awesome, <a href="/blog/ws/2015/02/02/ppc-ad-headlines">ultra-clickable headlines</a>).</li>
</ul>
<p>Awesome, <strong>now you have users engaging with your top-funnel content</strong>. The next question is, how do you usher them further down the funnel? We want them to keep eating that ice cream cone!</p>
<h2>Exchanging Info for Content</h2>
<p>Nothing in this world is free, and users understand that theyâ€™ll probably need to surrender some info in exchange for high-quality content.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="4eb2931f-f8cb-4453-84d4-9356048b8946" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/marketing-funnel-stages.png" alt="marketing funnel stages" width="581" height="258" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><em>example from </em><em><a href="http://blog.spoongraphics.co.uk/">spoongraphics</a></em></p>
<p>For high-value resources, ask users for their contact infomation (for most, an email address is ideal) in exchange for your content. Achieve this by <strong>crafting tailored landing pages for your most valuable resources.</strong></p>
<p>On the landing page, give a brief overview of what the user can expect from your content. For example:</p>
<ul>
<li>If youâ€™re offering <strong>a collection of free art vectors</strong>, explain what kind of art theyâ€™ll get, the format it will come in, and any licensing info.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><strong>For an ebook</strong>, explain what the ebook covers, and recap what theyâ€™ll learn.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="2af5812f-2108-4656-b6c7-c022cc53eae3" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/marketing-funnel-system.png" alt="marketing funnel system" width="499" height="574" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>example from </em><a href="http://www.quicksprout.com"><em>QuickSprout</em></a></p>
<p>Another method some marketers use for <a href="/blog/ws/2014/05/05/longform-content">longer-form</a> blog posts is to <strong>provide 95% of the content for free</strong>, with extra bonus content users can obtain by joining your mailing list. For example, a post with â€œ10 Quick and Easy Paleo Recipesâ€ may have an offer at the bottom of the post, promising 3 bonus recipes that will be emailed to them if they sign up for the mailing list.</p>
<h2>An Example of Great Top-Funnel Content</h2>
<p>Iâ€™m going to give you one specific, unusual example of <strong>top-funnel content that got <em>me</em> to take out my wallet</strong>. Thatâ€™s a pretty big deal because Iâ€™m a nearly notorious cheapskate.</p>
<p>Itâ€™s an example from a YouTuber by the name of ComicBookGirl19.</p>
<p>OK, at risk of making it public what a huge nerd I am, I watch a lot of <em>Game of Thrones</em> YouTube videos.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="1bf2466f-eaa0-43c6-9b7f-8239cd8e075f" data-langcode="en">
