<p>Granted, ComicBookGirl19â€™s marketing funnel is much more truncated than those of traditional services and products, but it still serves as a golden example of how <strong>introducing quality free content to a user can later convince them to convert</strong>.</p>
<h2>Middle of the Funnel: Up the Ante With More Targeted Assets</h2>
<p>In the middle of the funnel, youâ€™ll begin nurturing the leads you obtained from your earlier top-funnel content efforts. This <strong>nurturing is often done through <a href="/blog/ws/2014/11/12/is-email-marketing-effective">email marketing</a></strong>, using contact information you obtained earlier to send users targeted content.</p>
<p><strong>Nurturing involves building your existing relationship with users</strong>. Theyâ€™ve sunk their teeth into your ice cream cone, now itâ€™s time to help them explore its flavors.</p>
<p>Slowly, when youâ€™re in the middle funnel, youâ€™ll want to <strong>trickle in targeted content that relates more closely to your product or service</strong>. Buying guides are a great example. It can be tricky to hit the right mark, as you want to be promoting high-value content, but still shouldnâ€™t come off as too salesy.</p>
<p>Hereâ€™s a great example â€“ letâ€™s imagine that you sell coffee grinders.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="97cd25cc-61ed-4b44-b0fc-c36a4fb8bd35" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/what-is-a-marketing-funnel.jpg" alt="what is a marketing funnel" width="1500" height="1443" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A top-of-funnel idea might be detailing the differences between light and dark roast coffee. <strong>The middle funnel</strong> might involve a content piece that talks about why fresh grinded coffee is better than pre-ground coffee. Youâ€™re explaining why a coffee grinder could be useful, but arenâ€™t directly pitching your product â€“ at least not yet.</p>
<p>The middle of the funnel is also where you may want to consider discreetly promoting <a href="/blog/ws/2015/05/05/customer-testimonials">user testimonials</a> and user-generated content. Youâ€™re gently steering your users towards reminders about why you rock, without rubbing their faces in it.</p>
<h2>Bottom of the Marketing Funnel: Itâ€™s Game Time</h2>
<p>When you hit the <a href="/blog/ws/2020/10/01/bottom-funnel-conversions">bottom of the funnel,</a> itâ€™s time to get selling! When people are ready to buy, their behavior changes:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>They use keywords with high commercial intent,</strong> so this is where you should be bidding high with information-rich PPC ads that deliver exactly what they want. Think <a href="/blog/ws/2014/04/14/google-shopping-ads">Shopping Ads</a> and other extensions and formats that provide lots of product and price info as well as images.</li>
<li><strong>They might just call you directly.</strong> Make sure you&#8217;re using click-to-call in your mobile ads (with <a href="/call-tracking">call tracking</a>, so you know where the calls are coming from) and have your phone number plastered all over your site.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>At the bottom of the marketing funnel, youâ€™ll be handing a lot off to your sales team. </strong>Your sales team probably helped with your research for developing some of your high-value content in the middle of the funnel (pieces like buying guides), but now theyâ€™ll be taking the reins by reaching out and getting in touch with leads ripe for the picking.</p>
<p>Using lead tracking software like Salesforce, you should be able to see which offers users have taken advantage of and where theyâ€™re engaging with you.</p>
<p>If theyâ€™ve engaged with some of your higher-value content, itâ€™s time to reach out and promote your product. Some bottom of the marketing funnel actions includes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Demos</li>
<li>Free Trials</li>
<li>Assessments</li>
<li>Promotional Offers</li>
</ul>
<h2>Marketing Funnel Conversions Ahoy And Looking Ahead</h2>
<p>Hopefully your bottom funnel actions are enough to get users to convert. However, that doesnâ€™t mean your job is over. You still need to <strong>work to retain customers</strong> and, ideally, <strong>get your new customers to promote you to their friends</strong> and family.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="b3f93daa-601e-4ef1-9cf2-5658e49b7773" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/marketing-funnels.jpg" alt="marketing funnels" width="640" height="426" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><em>Wait until I tell you guys about this awesome tree I found</em></p>
<p>Remember, <strong>92% of customers say they trust word of mouth over any other form of online advertising.</strong> Consider setting up a referral program to encourage current customers to introduce you to new users.</p>
<p>Stay on your customersâ€™ good side by continuing to provide value and top-notch customers service. And thatâ€™s how you create a great marketing funnel that will keep users licking to the bottom of the cone.</p>
