<h2>1. Button Positioning: How Low Can (Or Should) You Go?</h2>
<p>When it comes to positioning, you have many, many options with social media buttons. You can put your social share buttons at:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Top of Post.</strong> Itâ€™s very common to place social media buttons at the top of blog posts.</li>
</ul>
<p>Some challenge this logic, asking <strong>â€œwill readers share a post they havenâ€™t even read yet?â€</strong> Bizarrely enough, <a href="http://www.theverge.com/2014/2/14/5411934/youre-not-going-to-read-this">some studies have shown</a> no real correlation between sharing a post and reading it. Itâ€™s very possible that users see an entrancing headline and decide right on the spot whether or not itâ€™s something worth sharing. Having social media buttons at the top of the page can alsoÂ <strong>act as <a href="/blog/ws/2017/01/10/social-proof-guide">social proof</a> and encourage readersÂ </strong>if you have tons of shares. If I see a post with +1,000 shares, it reinforces my belief that this article is awesome and worth taking the time to read.</p>
<div style="text-align:center;"><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/social-media-button-choices.png" alt="social media button choices" width="1054" height="192" /></div>
